The defendant Susan J Johnson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manuf/Deliver Schedule I, II Narcotics, a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

If discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  Collections may include income assignment.

Defendant Susan J Johnson in court with attorney M. Elizabeth Weathers.  Susan Opper appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Case called for Motion Hearing regarding Daubert Motion. No opening statement by either side. Exhibit #1 is marked. Dr. O'Donnell is sworn-in and testifies on behalf of the Defense. Atty Weathers requests that the Court recognize Dr. O'Donnell as an expert the Field of Clinical Pharmocology. Court grants request. Exhibit #2 is marked. Cross examination by the State. Dr. O'Donnell provides the State with notes, as requested by Atty Opper (marked as exhibit #3). Re-direct by Atty Weathers. No re-cross by the State. All 3 exhibits moved into evidence. Closing statements made by both parties. Court orders that Dr. O'Donnell may testify, but may not testify as to anything that would amount to vouching for the Defendant's credibility.
